<cell id="cell-0"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type># Lab 3.9 — LlamaIndex reveal
You have hand-rolled every piece of RAG across 3.1-3.8. Now see what a framework does
with the same corpus. Then watch it bite.
Reuses 03-naive-rag/data/arxiv/ + eval_questions.json. Cost: ~$0.05.</cell id="cell-0">
<cell id="cell-1">!uv add llama-index-core llama-index-llms-anthropic llama-index-embeddings-voyageai llama-index-retrievers-bm25 voyageai numpy</cell id="cell-1">
<cell id="cell-2"># The 15-line version — SimpleDirectoryReader + VectorStoreIndex + as_query_engine.
from llama_index.core import Settings, SimpleDirectoryReader, VectorStoreIndex
from llama_index.llms.anthropic import Anthropic
from llama_index.embeddings.voyageai import VoyageEmbedding

Settings.llm = Anthropic(model="claude-sonnet-4-6")
Settings.embed_model = VoyageEmbedding(model_name="voyage-3")

docs = SimpleDirectoryReader("../03-naive-rag/data/arxiv").load_data()
index = VectorStoreIndex.from_documents(docs)
engine = index.as_query_engine(similarity_top_k=5)

print(engine.query("What is chain-of-thought prompting?"))
# Answer + source nodes. Three dependencies and a cached index. The 50 lines of
# 3.3 collapsed into this.</cell id="cell-2">
<cell id="cell-3"># Parity check on the 20-Q arXiv eval.
from solution import build_naive_retriever, build_llamaindex_retriever, eval_retriever
import json
eval_set = json.load(open("../03-naive-rag/data/eval_questions.json"))
print("naive       nDCG@10 =", round(eval_retriever(build_naive_retriever(), eval_set, 10), 3))
print("llamaindex  nDCG@10 =", round(eval_retriever(build_llamaindex_retriever(), eval_set, 10), 3))
# Expected: both land near 0.68-0.72. LlamaIndex matches naive because
# SimpleDirectoryReader + default SentenceSplitter is doing a fine but *different*
# chunking than the 500-char fixed window. The numbers are close, not identical.</cell id="cell-3">
<cell id="cell-4"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>## Abstraction 1 — the node parser hides your chunker
`SimpleDirectoryReader` uses `SentenceSplitter` with `chunk_size=1024, overlap=20`
by default. On arXiv abstracts this gives ~1 chunk per paper, which happens to work.
On a 10-K filing with explicit section headings (`ITEM 1A. RISK FACTORS`), the
default sentence splitter crosses the heading boundary and produces chunks that
mix sections. Our 3.5 structural chunker never does this. To get 3.5 behavior in
LlamaIndex you override `transformations=[MarkdownNodeParser()]` or write a
custom `NodeParser` — which is the 50 lines you were hoping to skip.</cell id="cell-4">
<cell id="cell-5"># Abstraction 2 — QueryFusionRetriever default `mode="simple"` averages raw scores.
# BM25 returns tf-idf magnitudes (unbounded), cosine returns [0,1]. Averaging is
# the exact bug 3.6 warned about; RRF is what you want. LlamaIndex default bites.
from llama_index.retrievers.bm25 import BM25Retriever
from llama_index.core.retrievers import QueryFusionRetriever

bm25 = BM25Retriever.from_defaults(index=index, similarity_top_k=10)
dense = index.as_retriever(similarity_top_k=10)

# Wrong (default mode — scale bug):
bad = QueryFusionRetriever([dense, bm25], mode="simple", num_queries=1, similarity_top_k=10)
# Right:
good = QueryFusionRetriever([dense, bm25], mode="reciprocal_rerank", num_queries=1, similarity_top_k=10)

q = "1e-4 learning rate decay"   # numeric query — BM25 wins, dense cosine is tiny
print("simple  :", [n.metadata.get("file_name") for n in bad.retrieve(q)[:3]])
print("rrf     :", [n.metadata.get("file_name") for n in good.retrieve(q)[:3]])</cell id="cell-5">
<cell id="cell-6"># Abstraction 3 — response_mode="compact" (the default) stuffs every retrieved
# node into ONE prompt. On long 10-K chunks (8k tokens each × top_k=10) this
# overflows Sonnet's input. LlamaIndex silently *truncates middle nodes* with no
# warning. You find out because your faithfulness tanks and you cannot figure out
# why — the retrieval was fine, the generator was reading truncated garbage.
# Fix: response_mode="tree_summarize" (recursive) or "refine" (sequential) — both
# avoid the single-prompt stuff. Try it on a small top_k first.
from llama_index.core.response_synthesizers import get_response_synthesizer
engine_safe = index.as_query_engine(similarity_top_k=5,
                                    response_synthesizer=get_response_synthesizer(response_mode="tree_summarize"))
print(engine_safe.query("Summarize the contributions across these papers."))</cell id="cell-6">
<cell id="cell-7"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>## When to reach for LlamaIndex
- **Prototype / exploration:** yes. 15 lines to see if the corpus is retrievable at all.
- **Production with quality bar:** only with every default overridden. At that point
  you have re-written the 50 lines in LlamaIndex idioms. Pick whichever you prefer
  to debug at 3am — the framework or the primitives.
- **Hiring answer:** "I used it for the first pass, measured, found the defaults
  regressed on [specific metric], and replaced [specific component] with a hand
  implementation. The rest of the LlamaIndex code stayed." This is the only
  acceptable framework answer in a RAG interview.</cell id="cell-7">
